---
import Prose from '../../layouts/Prose.astro';
import QuoteList from '../../components/QuoteList.astro';
import { TECHNIQUES } from '../../lib/techniques';

const t = TECHNIQUES.find((x) => x.slug === 'springing-of-figures')!;
---

<Prose
  title={t.title}
  description={t.description}
  crumbs={[{ name: 'Techniques', href: '/techniques/' }, { name: t.title }]}
  kicker="Technique"
  jsonLd={[{ '@type': 'Article', headline: t.title }]}
>
  <p>
    Because the later figures of a chart are generated from the earlier ones, the same figure
    commonly appears in several houses. The old authors read this repetition (the
    <em>springing</em> or passing of a figure from one house into another) as the question
    spreading its roots: the houses into which the significator springs name the persons and
    matters entangled in the affair.
  </p>
  <QuoteList topic="springing" noFigures />
  <p>
    Cattan and Heydon also give the meaning of each figure's passing house by house, quoted on
    each <a href="/figures/">figure's own page</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Thus in Agrippa's example, the figure of the second house (money) found again in the sixth
    (servants) shows a thief within the household. Crowley applies the same rule in his worked
    example: see <a href="/library/crowley/method-of-judging/">the General Method of Judging a
    Figure</a>.
  </p>
</Prose>
